The broom package

Although most functions use data in a tidy format for input, often the output is messy.

That is, the output is easy for humans to read but not for computers.

Figure from https://opr.princeton.edu/workshops/Downloads/2016Jan_BroomRobinson.pdf

summary(fit) contains

  • coefficient-level information, including the estimate, standard error, and p-value, about each of the intercept, wt, and qsec terms.
  • observation-level information, such as the residuals and fitted values
  • model-level information in the form of \(R^2\), adjusted \(R^2\), an F statistic, and a p-value for the whole dataset.

The broom package contains three functions to generate corresponding data frames:

  • tidy()—component level
  • augment()—observation level
  • glance()—model level

library(broom)
tidy(fit)
## # A tibble: 3 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value

class(tidy(fit))

  • The broom package works with various methods, including lm(), glm(), and t.test(). Not all the broom functions make sense in all contexts (e.g., augment() with t.test()).
  • I find the broom package most useful when I’ve got more steps in my analyses. E.g.,
    • I’m fitting several models to the same data and want to create a single table of coefficients and such
    • I’m fitting the same model to subgroups.

Using broom for subgroup analyses

# The do() function from dplyr allows for any computation and returns a data frame
regressions <- mtcars %>% 
  group_by(am) %>%
    do(tidy(lm(mpg ~ wt + qsec, data = .), conf.int = TRUE))
regressions

Examples from Robinson, D. (2014). broom: An R Package for Converting Statistical Analysis Objects Into Tidy Data Frames. arXiv preprint arXiv:1412.3565. 

regressions %>% filter(term != "(Intercept)") %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = estimate, y = term, color = factor(am))) +
    geom_point() + geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0)

Look at a single linear regression of log of salary against batting average, controlling for year.

ggplot(merged, aes(average, salary, color = yearID)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10()

  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() + 
  geom_smooth()

Could this vary by team?

    do(tidy(lm(log10(salary) ~ average + yearID, .), conf.int = TRUE))

It’s now easy to examine the results visually.

coefs <- team_regressions %>% ungroup() %>%
    filter(term == "average") %>%
    mutate(teamID = reorder(teamID, estimate))

ggplot(coefs, aes(x = estimate, y = teamID)) + geom_point() +
    geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "red")
